===Noun===
'''rascal'''
# Someone who is [[naughty]]; a [[troublemaker]]
#:''If you have deer in the area, you may have to put a fence around your garden to keep the '''rascals''' out.''

===Word History===
Recorded since c.1330, as rascaile "people of the lowest class, [[rabble]] of an [[army]]", derived from Old French ''rascaille'' "outcast, rabble" (12c.; modern French [[racaille]]), perhaps from rasque "mud, filth, scab, dregs," from Vulgar Latin *rasicare "to scrape": Rascal meant the  The singular form is first attested in 1461; the present extended sense of "low, dishonest person" is from early 1586.

